#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:10
msgid "Basic Usage"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:12
msgid ""
"The ``spack`` command has many *subcommands*.  You'll only need a small "
"subset of them for typical usage."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:15
msgid ""
"Note that Spack colorizes output.  ``less -R`` should be used with Spack to "
"maintain this colorization.  E.g.:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:18
msgid "$ spack find | less -R"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:22
msgid "It is recommended that the following be put in your ``.bashrc`` file:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:24
msgid "alias less='less -R'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:28
msgid ""
"If you do not see colorized output when using ``less -R`` it is because "
"color is being disabled in the piped output. In this case, tell spack to "
"force colorized output with a flag"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:32
msgid "$ spack --color always find | less -R"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:36
msgid "or an environment variable"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:38
msgid "$ SPACK_COLOR=always spack find | less -R"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:44
msgid "Listing available packages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:46
msgid ""
"To install software with Spack, you need to know what software is "
"available.  You can see a list of available package names at the `packages."
"spack.io <https://packages.spack.io>`_ website, or using the ``spack list`` "
"command."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:55
msgid "``spack list``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:57
msgid ""
"The ``spack list`` command prints out a list of all of the packages Spack "
"can install:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:63
msgid ""
"There are thousands of them, so we've truncated the output above, but you "
"can find a `full list here <https://packages.spack.io>`_. Packages are "
"listed by name in alphabetical order. A pattern to match with no wildcards, "
"``*`` or ``?``, will be treated as though it started and ended with ``*``, "
"so ``util`` is equivalent to ``*util*``.  All patterns will be treated as "
"case-insensitive. You can also add the ``-d`` to search the description of "
"the package in addition to the name.  Some examples:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:72
msgid "All packages whose names contain \"sql\":"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:76
msgid "All packages whose names or descriptions contain documentation:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:84
msgid "``spack info``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:86
msgid ""
"To get more information on a particular package from `spack list`, use "
"`spack info`.  Just supply the name of a package:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:91
msgid ""
"Most of the information is self-explanatory.  The *safe versions* are "
"versions that Spack knows the checksum for, and it will use the checksum to "
"verify that these versions download without errors or viruses."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:96
msgid ""
":ref:`Dependencies <sec-specs>` and :ref:`virtual dependencies <sec-virtual-"
"dependencies>` are described in more detail later."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:103
msgid "``spack versions``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:105
msgid ""
"To see *more* available versions of a package, run ``spack versions``. For "
"example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:110
msgid ""
"There are two sections in the output.  *Safe versions* are versions for "
"which Spack has a checksum on file.  It can verify that these versions are "
"downloaded correctly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:114
msgid ""
"In many cases, Spack can also show you what versions are available out on "
"the web---these are *remote versions*.  Spack gets this information by "
"scraping it directly from package web pages.  Depending on the package and "
"how its releases are organized, Spack may or may not be able to find remote "
"versions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:122
msgid "Installing and uninstalling"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:128
msgid "``spack install``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:130
msgid ""
"``spack install`` will install any package shown by ``spack list``. For "
"example, To install the latest version of the ``mpileaks`` package, you "
"might type this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:134 ../../../basic_usage.rst:1593
msgid "$ spack install mpileaks"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:138
msgid ""
"If ``mpileaks`` depends on other packages, Spack will install the "
"dependencies first.  It then fetches the ``mpileaks`` tarball, expands it, "
"verifies that it was downloaded without errors, builds it, and installs it "
"in its own directory under ``$SPACK_ROOT/opt``. You'll see a number of "
"messages from Spack, a lot of build output, and a message that the package "
"is installed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:145
msgid ""
"$ spack install mpileaks\n"
"... dependency build output ...\n"
"==> Installing mpileaks-1.0-ph7pbnhl334wuhogmugriohcwempqry2\n"
"==> No binary for mpileaks-1.0-ph7pbnhl334wuhogmugriohcwempqry2 found: "
"installing from source\n"
"==> mpileaks: Executing phase: 'autoreconf'\n"
"==> mpileaks: Executing phase: 'configure'\n"
"==> mpileaks: Executing phase: 'build'\n"
"==> mpileaks: Executing phase: 'install'\n"
"[+] ~/spack/opt/linux-rhel7-broadwell/gcc-8.1.0/mpileaks-1.0-"
"ph7pbnhl334wuhogmugriohcwempqry2"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:157
msgid ""
"The last line, with the ``[+]``, indicates where the package is installed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:160
msgid ""
"Add the Spack debug option (one or more times) -- ``spack -d install "
"mpileaks`` -- to get additional (and even more verbose) output."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:165
msgid "Building a specific version"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:167
msgid ""
"Spack can also build *specific versions* of a package.  To do this, just add "
"``@`` after the package name, followed by a version:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:170
msgid "$ spack install mpich@3.0.4"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:174
msgid ""
"Any number of versions of the same package can be installed at once without "
"interfering with each other.  This is good for multi-user sites, as "
"installing a version that one user needs will not disrupt existing "
"installations for other users."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:179
msgid ""
"In addition to different versions, Spack can customize the compiler, compile-"
"time options (variants), compiler flags, and platform (for cross compiles) "
"of an installation.  Spack is unique in that it can also configure the "
"*dependencies* a package is built with.  For example, two configurations of "
"the same version of a package, one built with boost 1.39.0, and the other "
"version built with version 1.43.0, can coexist."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:186
msgid ""
"This can all be done on the command line using the *spec* syntax. Spack "
"calls the descriptor used to refer to a particular package configuration a "
"**spec**.  In the commands above, ``mpileaks`` and ``mpileaks@3.0.4`` are "
"both valid *specs*.  We'll talk more about how you can use them to customize "
"an installation in :ref:`sec-specs`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:194
msgid "Reusing installed dependencies"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:196
msgid ""
"By default, when you run ``spack install``, Spack tries hard to reuse "
"existing installations as dependencies, either from a local store or from "
"remote buildcaches if configured. This minimizes unwanted rebuilds of common "
"dependencies, in particular if you update Spack frequently."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:201
msgid ""
"In case you want the latest versions and configurations to be installed "
"instead, you can add the ``--fresh`` option:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:204
msgid "$ spack install --fresh mpich"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:208
msgid ""
"Reusing installations in this mode is \"accidental\", and happening only if "
"there's a match between existing installations and what Spack would have "
"installed anyhow."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:212
msgid ""
"You can use the ``spack spec -I mpich`` command to see what will be reused "
"and what will be built before you install."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:215
msgid ""
"You can configure Spack to use the ``--fresh`` behavior by default in "
"``concretizer.yaml``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:218
msgid ""
"concretizer:\n"
"  reuse: false"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:227
msgid "``spack uninstall``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:229
msgid ""
"To uninstall a package, type ``spack uninstall <package>``.  This will ask "
"the user for confirmation before completely removing the directory in which "
"the package was installed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:233 ../../../basic_usage.rst:252
msgid "$ spack uninstall mpich"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:237
msgid ""
"If there are still installed packages that depend on the package to be "
"uninstalled, spack will refuse to uninstall it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:240
msgid ""
"To uninstall a package and every package that depends on it, you may give "
"the ``--dependents`` option."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:243
msgid "$ spack uninstall --dependents mpich"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:247
msgid ""
"will display a list of all the packages that depend on ``mpich`` and, upon "
"confirmation, will uninstall them in the right order."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:250
msgid "A command like"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:256
msgid ""
"may be ambiguous if multiple ``mpich`` configurations are installed. For "
"example, if both ``mpich@3.0.2`` and ``mpich@3.1`` are installed, ``mpich`` "
"could refer to either one. Because it cannot determine which one to "
"uninstall, Spack will ask you either to provide a version number to remove "
"the ambiguity or use the ``--all`` option to uninstall all of the matching "
"packages."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:263
msgid "You may force uninstall a package with the ``--force`` option"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:265
msgid "$ spack uninstall --force mpich"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:269
msgid ""
"but you risk breaking other installed packages. In general, it is safer to "
"remove dependent packages *before* removing their dependencies or use the "
"``--dependents`` option."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:278
msgid "Garbage collection"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:280
msgid ""
"When Spack builds software from sources, if often installs tools that are "
"needed just to build or test other software. These are not necessary at "
"runtime. To support cases where removing these tools can be a benefit Spack "
"provides the ``spack gc`` (\"garbage collector\") command, which will "
"uninstall all unneeded packages:"
msgstr ""

