#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:515
msgid ""
"Packages are divided into groups according to their architecture and "
"compiler.  Within each group, Spack tries to keep the view simple, and only "
"shows the version of installed packages."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:523
msgid "Viewing more metadata"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:525
msgid ""
"``spack find`` can filter the package list based on the package name, spec, "
"or a number of properties of their installation status.  For example, "
"missing dependencies of a spec can be shown with ``--missing``, deprecated "
"packages can be included with ``--deprecated``, packages which were "
"explicitly installed with ``spack install <package>`` can be singled out "
"with ``--explicit`` and those which have been pulled in only as dependencies "
"with ``--implicit``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:534
msgid ""
"In some cases, there may be different configurations of the *same* version "
"of a package installed.  For example, there are two installations of "
"``libdwarf@20130729`` above.  We can look at them in more detail using "
"``spack find --deps``, and by asking only to show ``libdwarf`` packages:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:540
msgid ""
"$ spack find --deps libdwarf\n"
"==> 2 installed packages.\n"
"-- linux-debian7-x86_64 / gcc@4.4.7 --------------------------------\n"
"    libdwarf@20130729-d9b90962\n"
"        ^libelf@0.8.12\n"
"    libdwarf@20130729-b52fac98\n"
"        ^libelf@0.8.13"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:550
msgid ""
"Now we see that the two instances of ``libdwarf`` depend on *different* "
"versions of ``libelf``: 0.8.12 and 0.8.13.  This view can become complicated "
"for packages with many dependencies.  If you just want to know whether two "
"packages' dependencies differ, you can use ``spack find --long``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:556
msgid ""
"$ spack find --long libdwarf\n"
"==> 2 installed packages.\n"
"-- linux-debian7-x86_64 / gcc@4.4.7 --------------------------------\n"
"libdwarf@20130729-d9b90962  libdwarf@20130729-b52fac98"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:563
msgid ""
"Now the ``libdwarf`` installs have hashes after their names.  These are "
"hashes over all of the dependencies of each package.  If the hashes are the "
"same, then the packages have the same dependency configuration."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:567
msgid ""
"If you want to know the path where each package is installed, you can use "
"``spack find --paths``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:570
msgid ""
"$ spack find --paths\n"
"==> 74 installed packages.\n"
"-- linux-debian7-x86_64 / gcc@4.4.7 --------------------------------\n"
"    ImageMagick@6.8.9-10  ~/spack/opt/linux-debian7-x86_64/gcc@4.4.7/"
"ImageMagick@6.8.9-10-4df950dd\n"
"    adept-utils@1.0       ~/spack/opt/linux-debian7-x86_64/gcc@4.4.7/adept-"
"utils@1.0-5adef8da\n"
"    atk@2.14.0            ~/spack/opt/linux-debian7-x86_64/gcc@4.4.7/"
"atk@2.14.0-3d09ac09\n"
"    boost@1.55.0          ~/spack/opt/linux-debian7-x86_64/gcc@4.4.7/"
"boost@1.55.0\n"
"    bzip2@1.0.6           ~/spack/opt/linux-debian7-x86_64/gcc@4.4.7/"
"bzip2@1.0.6\n"
"    cairo@1.14.0          ~/spack/opt/linux-debian7-x86_64/gcc@4.4.7/"
"cairo@1.14.0-fcc2ab44\n"
"    callpath@1.0.2        ~/spack/opt/linux-debian7-x86_64/gcc@4.4.7/"
"callpath@1.0.2-5dce4318\n"
"..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:584
msgid ""
"You can restrict your search to a particular package by supplying its name:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:587
msgid ""
"$ spack find --paths libelf\n"
"-- linux-debian7-x86_64 / gcc@4.4.7 --------------------------------\n"
"    libelf@0.8.11  ~/spack/opt/linux-debian7-x86_64/gcc@4.4.7/libelf@0.8.11\n"
"    libelf@0.8.12  ~/spack/opt/linux-debian7-x86_64/gcc@4.4.7/libelf@0.8.12\n"
"    libelf@0.8.13  ~/spack/opt/linux-debian7-x86_64/gcc@4.4.7/libelf@0.8.13"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:597
msgid "Spec queries"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:599
msgid ""
"``spack find`` actually does a lot more than this.  You can use *specs* to "
"query for specific configurations and builds of each package. If you want to "
"find only libelf versions greater than version 0.8.12, you could say:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:604
msgid ""
"$ spack find libelf@0.8.12:\n"
"-- linux-debian7-x86_64 / gcc@4.4.7 --------------------------------\n"
"    libelf@0.8.12  libelf@0.8.13"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:610
msgid ""
"Finding just the versions of libdwarf built with a particular version of "
"libelf would look like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:613
msgid ""
"$ spack find --long libdwarf ^libelf@0.8.12\n"
"==> 1 installed packages.\n"
"-- linux-debian7-x86_64 / gcc@4.4.7 --------------------------------\n"
"libdwarf@20130729-d9b90962"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:620
msgid ""
"We can also search for packages that have a certain attribute. For example, "
"``spack find libdwarf +debug`` will show only installations of libdwarf with "
"the 'debug' compile-time option enabled."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:624
msgid "The full spec syntax is discussed in detail in :ref:`sec-specs`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:629
msgid "Machine-readable output"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:631
msgid ""
"If you only want to see very specific things about installed packages, Spack "
"has some options for you.  ``spack find --format`` can be used to output "
"only specific fields:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:635
msgid ""
"$ spack find --format \"{name}-{version}-{hash}\"\n"
"autoconf-2.69-icynozk7ti6h4ezzgonqe6jgw5f3ulx4\n"
"automake-1.16.1-o5v3tc77kesgonxjbmeqlwfmb5qzj7zy\n"
"bzip2-1.0.6-syohzw57v2jfag5du2x4bowziw3m5p67\n"
"bzip2-1.0.8-zjny4jwfyvzbx6vii3uuekoxmtu6eyuj\n"
"cmake-3.15.1-7cf6onn52gywnddbmgp7qkil4hdoxpcb\n"
"..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:645
msgid "or:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:647
msgid ""
"$ spack find --format \"{hash:7}\"\n"
"icynozk\n"
"o5v3tc7\n"
"syohzw5\n"
"zjny4jw\n"
"7cf6onn\n"
"..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:657
msgid ""
"This uses the same syntax as described in documentation for :meth:`~spack."
"spec.Spec.format` -- you can use any of the options there. This is useful "
"for passing metadata about packages to other command-line tools."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:662
msgid ""
"Alternately, if you want something even more machine readable, you can "
"output each spec as JSON records using ``spack find --json``.  This will "
"output metadata on specs and all dependencies as json:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:666
msgid ""
"$ spack find --json sqlite@3.28.0\n"
"[\n"
" {\n"
"  \"name\": \"sqlite\",\n"
"  \"hash\": \"3ws7bsihwbn44ghf6ep4s6h4y2o6eznv\",\n"
"  \"version\": \"3.28.0\",\n"
"  \"arch\": {\n"
"   \"platform\": \"darwin\",\n"
"   \"platform_os\": \"mojave\",\n"
"   \"target\": \"x86_64\"\n"
"  },\n"
"  \"compiler\": {\n"
"   \"name\": \"apple-clang\",\n"
"   \"version\": \"10.0.0\"\n"
"  },\n"
"  \"namespace\": \"builtin\",\n"
"  \"parameters\": {\n"
"   \"fts\": true,\n"
"   \"functions\": false,\n"
"   \"cflags\": [],\n"
"   \"cppflags\": [],\n"
"   \"cxxflags\": [],\n"
"   \"fflags\": [],\n"
"   \"ldflags\": [],\n"
"   \"ldlibs\": []\n"
"  },\n"
"  \"dependencies\": {\n"
"   \"readline\": {\n"
"    \"hash\": \"722dzmgymxyxd6ovjvh4742kcetkqtfs\",\n"
"    \"type\": [\n"
"     \"build\",\n"
"     \"link\"\n"
"    ]\n"
"   }\n"
"  }\n"
" },\n"
" ...\n"
"]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:707
msgid ""
"You can use this with tools like `jq <https://stedolan.github.io/jq/>`_ to "
"quickly create JSON records structured the way you want:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:710
msgid ""
"$ spack find --json sqlite@3.28.0 | jq -C '.[] | { name, version, hash }'\n"
"{\n"
"  \"name\": \"sqlite\",\n"
"  \"version\": \"3.28.0\",\n"
"  \"hash\": \"3ws7bsihwbn44ghf6ep4s6h4y2o6eznv\"\n"
"}\n"
"{\n"
"  \"name\": \"readline\",\n"
"  \"version\": \"7.0\",\n"
"  \"hash\": \"722dzmgymxyxd6ovjvh4742kcetkqtfs\"\n"
"}\n"
"{\n"
"  \"name\": \"ncurses\",\n"
"  \"version\": \"6.1\",\n"
"  \"hash\": \"zvaa4lhlhilypw5quj3akyd3apbq5gap\"\n"
"}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:732
msgid "``spack diff``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:734
msgid ""
"It's often the case that you have two versions of a spec that you need to "
"disambiguate. Let's say that we've installed two variants of zlib, one with "
"and one without the optimize variant:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:738
msgid ""
"$ spack install zlib\n"
"$ spack install zlib -optimize"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:743
msgid "When we do ``spack find`` we see the two versions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:745
msgid ""
"$ spack find zlib\n"
"==> 2 installed packages\n"
"-- linux-ubuntu20.04-skylake / gcc@9.3.0 ------------------------\n"
"zlib@1.2.11  zlib@1.2.11"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:753
msgid ""
"Let's now say that we want to uninstall zlib. We run the command, and hit a "
"problem real quickly since we have two!"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:756
msgid ""
"$ spack uninstall zlib\n"
"==> Error: zlib matches multiple packages:\n"
"\n"
"    -- linux-ubuntu20.04-skylake / gcc@9.3.0 ------------------------\n"
"    efzjziy zlib@1.2.11  sl7m27m zlib@1.2.11\n"
"\n"
"==> Error: You can either:\n"
"    a) use a more specific spec, or\n"
"    b) specify the spec by its hash (e.g. `spack uninstall /hash`), or\n"
"    c) use `spack uninstall --all` to uninstall ALL matching specs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:769
msgid ""
"Oh no! We can see from the above that we have two different versions of zlib "
"installed, and the only difference between the two is the hash. This is a "
"good use case for ``spack diff``, which can easily show us the \"diff\" or "
"set difference between properties for two packages. Let's try it out. Since "
"the only difference we see in the ``spack find`` view is the hash, let's use "
"``spack diff`` to look for more detail. We will provide the two hashes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:776
msgid ""
"$ spack diff /efzjziy /sl7m27m\n"
"==> Warning: This interface is subject to change.\n"
"\n"
"--- zlib@1.2.11efzjziyc3dmb5h5u5azsthgbgog5mj7g\n"
"+++ zlib@1.2.11sl7m27mzkbejtkrajigj3a3m37ygv4u2\n"
"@@ variant_value @@\n"
"-  zlib optimize False\n"
"+  zlib optimize True"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:788
msgid ""
"The output is colored, and written in the style of a git diff. This means "
"that you can copy and paste it into a GitHub markdown as a code block with "
"language \"diff\" and it will render nicely! Here is an example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:792
msgid ""
"```diff\n"
"--- zlib@1.2.11/efzjziyc3dmb5h5u5azsthgbgog5mj7g\n"
"+++ zlib@1.2.11/sl7m27mzkbejtkrajigj3a3m37ygv4u2\n"
"@@ variant_value @@\n"
"-  zlib optimize False\n"
"+  zlib optimize True\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:802
msgid ""
"Awesome! Now let's read the diff. It tells us that our first zlib was built "
"with ``~optimize`` (``False``) and the second was built with ``+optimize`` "
"(``True``). You can't see it in the docs here, but the output above is also "
"colored based on the content being an addition (+) or subtraction (-)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:807
msgid ""
"This is a small example, but you will be able to see differences for any "
"attributes on the installation spec. Running ``spack diff A B`` means we'll "
"see which spec attributes are on ``B`` but not on ``A`` (green) and which "
"are on ``A`` but not on ``B`` (red). Here is another example with an "
"additional difference type, ``version``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:812
msgid ""
"$ spack diff python@2.7.8 python@3.8.11\n"
"==> Warning: This interface is subject to change.\n"
"\n"
"--- python@2.7.8/tsxdi6gl4lihp25qrm4d6nys3nypufbf\n"
"+++ python@3.8.11/yjtseru4nbpllbaxb46q7wfkyxbuvzxx\n"
"@@ variant_value @@\n"
"-  python patches "
"a8c52415a8b03c0e5f28b5d52ae498f7a7e602007db2b9554df28cd5685839b8\n"
"+  python patches "
"0d98e93189bc278fbc37a50ed7f183bd8aaf249a8e1670a465f0db6bb4f8cf87\n"
"@@ version @@\n"
"-  openssl 1.0.2u\n"
"+  openssl 1.1.1k\n"
"-  python 2.7.8\n"
"+  python 3.8.11"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:828
msgid ""
"Let's say that we were only interested in one kind of attribute above, "
"``version``. We can ask the command to only output this attribute.  To do "
"this, you'd add the ``--attribute`` for attribute parameter, which defaults "
"to all. Here is how you would filter to show just versions:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:833
msgid ""
"$ spack diff --attribute version python@2.7.8 python@3.8.11\n"
"==> Warning: This interface is subject to change.\n"
"\n"
"--- python@2.7.8/tsxdi6gl4lihp25qrm4d6nys3nypufbf\n"
"+++ python@3.8.11/yjtseru4nbpllbaxb46q7wfkyxbuvzxx\n"
"@@ version @@\n"
"-  openssl 1.0.2u\n"
"+  openssl 1.1.1k\n"
"-  python 2.7.8\n"
"+  python 3.8.11"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:846
msgid ""
"And you can add as many attributes as you'd like with multiple `--attribute` "
"arguments (for lots of attributes, you can use ``-a`` for short). Finally, "
"if you want to view the data as json (and possibly pipe into an output file) "
"just add ``--json``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:851
msgid "$ spack diff --json python@2.7.8 python@3.8.11"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:856
msgid ""
"This data will be much longer because along with the differences for ``A`` "
"vs. ``B`` and ``B`` vs. ``A``, the JSON output also showsthe intersection."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:862
msgid "Using installed packages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:864
msgid ""
"There are several different ways to use Spack packages once you have "
"installed them. As you've seen, spack packages are installed into long paths "
"with hashes, and you need a way to get them into your path. The easiest way "
"is to use :ref:`spack load <cmd-spack-load>`, which is described in this "
"section."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:870
msgid "Some more advanced ways to use Spack packages include:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:872
msgid ""
":ref:`environments <environments>`, which you can use to bundle a number of "
"related packages to \"activate\" all at once, and"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:874
msgid ""
":ref:`environment modules <modules>`, which are commonly used on "
"supercomputing clusters. Spack generates module files for every installation "
"automatically, and you can customize how this is done."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:882
msgid "``spack load / unload``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:884
msgid ""
"If you have :ref:`shell support <shell-support>` enabled you can use the "
"``spack load`` command to quickly get a package on your ``PATH``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:887
msgid ""
"For example this will add the ``mpich`` package built with ``gcc`` to your "
"path:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:890
msgid ""
"$ spack install mpich %gcc@4.4.7\n"
"\n"
"# ... wait for install ...\n"
"\n"
"$ spack load mpich %gcc@4.4.7\n"
"$ which mpicc\n"
"~/spack/opt/linux-debian7-x86_64/gcc@4.4.7/mpich@3.0.4/bin/mpicc"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:900
msgid ""
"These commands will add appropriate directories to your ``PATH`` and "
"``MANPATH`` according to the :ref:`prefix inspections <customize-env-"
"modifications>` defined in your modules configuration. When you no longer "
"want to use a package, you can type unload or unuse similarly:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:907
msgid "$ spack unload mpich %gcc@4.4.7"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:914
msgid "Ambiguous specs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:916
msgid ""
"If a spec used with load/unload or is ambiguous (i.e. more than one "
"installed package matches it), then Spack will warn you:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:919
msgid ""
"$ spack load libelf\n"
"==> Error: libelf matches multiple packages.\n"
"Matching packages:\n"
"  qmm4kso libelf@0.8.13%gcc@4.4.7 arch=linux-debian7-x86_64\n"
"  cd2u6jt libelf@0.8.13%intel@15.0.0 arch=linux-debian7-x86_64\n"
"Use a more specific spec"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:928
msgid ""
"You can either type the ``spack load`` command again with a fully qualified "
"argument, or you can add just enough extra constraints to identify one "
"package.  For example, above, the key differentiator is that one ``libelf`` "
"is built with the Intel compiler, while the other used ``gcc``.  You could "
"therefore just type:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:934
msgid "$ spack load libelf %intel"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:938
msgid ""
"To identify just the one built with the Intel compiler. If you want to be "
"*very* specific, you can load it by its hash. For example, to load the first "
"``libelf`` above, you would run:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:942
msgid "$ spack load /qmm4kso"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:946
msgid ""
"To see which packages that you have loaded to your environment you would use "
"``spack find --loaded``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:949
msgid ""
"$ spack find --loaded\n"
"==> 2 installed packages\n"
"-- linux-debian7 / gcc@4.4.7 ------------------------------------\n"
"libelf@0.8.13\n"
"\n"
"-- linux-debian7 / intel@15.0.0 ---------------------------------\n"
"libelf@0.8.13"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:959
msgid ""
"You can also use ``spack load --list`` to get the same output, but it does "
"not have the full set of query options that ``spack find`` offers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:962
msgid ""
"We'll learn more about Spack's spec syntax in :ref:`a later section <sec-"
"specs>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:969
msgid "Python packages and virtual environments"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:971
msgid ""
"Spack can install a large number of Python packages. Their names are "
"typically prefixed with ``py-``. Installing and using them is no different "
"from any other package:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:975
msgid ""
"$ spack install py-numpy\n"
"$ spack load py-numpy\n"
"$ python3\n"
">>> import numpy"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:982
msgid ""
"The ``spack load`` command sets the ``PATH`` variable so that the right "
"Python executable is used, and makes sure that ``numpy`` and its "
"dependencies can be located in the ``PYTHONPATH``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:986
msgid ""
"Spack is different from other Python package managers in that it installs "
"every package into its *own* prefix. This is in contrast to ``pip``, which "
"installs all packages into the same prefix, be it in a virtual environment "
"or not."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:991
msgid ""
"For many users, **virtual environments** are more convenient than repeated "
"``spack load`` commands, particularly when working with multiple Python "
"packages. Fortunately Spack supports environments itself, which together "
"with a view are no different from Python virtual environments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:996
msgid ""
"The recommended way of working with Python extensions such as ``py-numpy`` "
"is through :ref:`Environments <environments>`. The following example creates "
"a Spack environment with ``numpy`` in the current working directory. It also "
"puts a filesystem view in ``./view``, which is a more traditional combined "
"prefix for all packages in the environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1002
msgid ""
"$ spack env create --with-view view --dir .\n"
"$ spack -e . add py-numpy\n"
"$ spack -e . concretize\n"
"$ spack -e . install"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1009
msgid "Now you can activate the environment and start using the packages:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1011
msgid ""
"$ spack env activate .\n"
"$ python3\n"
">>> import numpy"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1017
msgid ""
"The environment view is also a virtual environment, which is useful if you "
"are sharing the environment with others who are unfamiliar with Spack. They "
"can either use the Python executable directly:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1021
msgid ""
"$ ./view/bin/python3\n"
">>> import numpy"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1026
msgid "or use the activation script:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1028
msgid ""
"$ source ./view/bin/activate\n"
"$ python3\n"
">>> import numpy"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1034
msgid ""
"In general, there should not be much difference between ``spack env "
"activate`` and using the virtual environment. The main advantage of ``spack "
"env activate`` is that it knows about more packages than just Python "
"packages, and it may set additional runtime variables that are not covered "
"by the virtual environment activation script."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1040
msgid ""
"See :ref:`environments` for a more in-depth description of Spack "
"environments and customizations to views."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1048
msgid "Specs & dependencies"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1050
msgid ""
"We know that ``spack install``, ``spack uninstall``, and other commands take "
"a package name with an optional version specifier.  In Spack, that "
"descriptor is called a *spec*.  Spack uses specs to refer to a particular "
"build configuration (or configurations) of a package. Specs are more than a "
"package name and a version; you can use them to specify the compiler, "
"compiler version, architecture, compile options, and dependency options for "
"a build.  In this section, we'll go over the full syntax of specs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1059
msgid "Here is an example of a much longer spec than we've seen thus far:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1061
msgid ""
"mpileaks @1.2:1.4 %gcc@4.7.5 +debug -qt target=x86_64 ^callpath @1.1 "
"%gcc@4.7.2"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1065
msgid ""
"If provided to ``spack install``, this will install the ``mpileaks`` library "
"at some version between ``1.2`` and ``1.4`` (inclusive), built using ``gcc`` "
"at version 4.7.5 for a generic ``x86_64`` architecture, with debug options "
"enabled, and without Qt support.  Additionally, it says to link it with the "
"``callpath`` library (which it depends on), and to build callpath with "
"``gcc`` 4.7.2.  Most specs will not be as complicated as this one, but this "
"is a good example of what is possible with specs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1074
msgid "More formally, a spec consists of the following pieces:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1076
msgid "Package name identifier (``mpileaks`` above)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1077
msgid "``@`` Optional version specifier (``@1.2:1.4``)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1078
msgid ""
"``%`` Optional compiler specifier, with an optional compiler version "
"(``gcc`` or ``gcc@4.7.3``)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1080
msgid ""
"``+`` or ``-`` or ``~`` Optional variant specifiers (``+debug``, ``-qt``, or "
"``~qt``) for boolean variants. Use ``++`` or ``--`` or ``~~`` to propagate "
"variants through the dependencies (``++debug``, ``--qt``, or ``~~qt``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1084
msgid ""
"``name=<value>`` Optional variant specifiers that are not restricted to "
"boolean variants. Use ``name==<value>`` to propagate variant through the "
"dependencies."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1087
msgid ""
"``name=<value>`` Optional compiler flag specifiers. Valid flag names are "
"``cflags``, ``cxxflags``, ``fflags``, ``cppflags``, ``ldflags``, and "
"``ldlibs``. Use ``name==<value>`` to propagate compiler flags through the "
"dependencies."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1090
msgid ""
"``target=<value> os=<value>`` Optional architecture specifier "
"(``target=haswell os=CNL10``)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1092
msgid "``^`` Dependency specs (``^callpath@1.1``)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1094
msgid ""
"There are two things to notice here.  The first is that specs are "
"recursively defined.  That is, each dependency after ``^`` is a spec "
"itself.  The second is that everything is optional *except* for the initial "
"package name identifier.  Users can be as vague or as specific as they want "
"about the details of building packages, and this makes spack good for "
"beginners and experts alike."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1101
msgid ""
"To really understand what's going on above, we need to think about how "
"software is structured.  An executable or a library (these are generally the "
"artifacts produced by building software) depends on other libraries in order "
"to run.  We can represent the relationship between a package and its "
"dependencies as a graph.  Here is the full dependency graph for ``mpileaks``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1118
msgid ""
"Each box above is a package and each arrow represents a dependency on some "
"other package.  For example, we say that the package ``mpileaks`` *depends "
"on* ``callpath`` and ``mpich``.  ``mpileaks`` also depends *indirectly* on "
"``dyninst``, ``libdwarf``, and ``libelf``, in that these libraries are "
"dependencies of ``callpath``.  To install ``mpileaks``, Spack has to build "
"all of these packages.  Dependency graphs in Spack have to be acyclic, and "
"the *depends on* relationship is directional, so this is a *directed, "
"acyclic graph* or *DAG*."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1127
msgid ""
"The package name identifier in the spec is the root of some dependency DAG, "
"and the DAG itself is implicit.  Spack knows the precise dependencies among "
"packages, but users do not need to know the full DAG structure. Each ``^`` "
"in the full spec refers to some dependency of the root package. Spack will "
"raise an error if you supply a name after ``^`` that the root does not "
"actually depend on (e.g. ``mpileaks ^emacs@23.3``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1135
msgid ""
"Spack further simplifies things by only allowing one configuration of each "
"package within any single build.  Above, both ``mpileaks`` and ``callpath`` "
"depend on ``mpich``, but ``mpich`` appears only once in the DAG.  You cannot "
"build an ``mpileaks`` version that depends on one version of ``mpich`` *and* "
"on a ``callpath`` version that depends on some *other* version of "
"``mpich``.  In general, such a configuration would likely behave "
"unexpectedly at runtime, and Spack enforces this to ensure a consistent "
"runtime environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1144
msgid ""
"The point of specs is to abstract this full DAG from Spack users.  If a user "
"does not care about the DAG at all, she can refer to mpileaks by simply "
"writing ``mpileaks``.  If she knows that ``mpileaks`` indirectly uses "
"``dyninst`` and she wants a particular version of ``dyninst``, then she can "
"refer to ``mpileaks ^dyninst@8.1``.  Spack will fill in the rest when it "
"parses the spec; the user only needs to know package names and minimal "
"details about their relationship."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1152
msgid ""
"When spack prints out specs, it sorts package names alphabetically to "
"normalize the way they are displayed, but users do not need to worry about "
"this when they write specs.  The only restriction on the order of "
"dependencies within a spec is that they appear *after* the root package.  "
"For example, these two specs represent exactly the same configuration:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1159
msgid ""
"mpileaks ^callpath@1.0 ^libelf@0.8.3\n"
"mpileaks ^libelf@0.8.3 ^callpath@1.0"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1164
msgid ""
"You can put all the same modifiers on dependency specs that you would put on "
"the root spec.  That is, you can specify their versions, compilers, "
"variants, and architectures just like any other spec. Specifiers are "
"associated with the nearest package name to their left. For example, above, "
"``@1.1`` and ``%gcc@4.7.2`` associates with the ``callpath`` package, while "
"``@1.2:1.4``, ``%gcc@4.7.5``, ``+debug``, ``-qt``, and ``target=haswell "
"os=CNL10`` all associate with the ``mpileaks`` package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1172
msgid ""
"In the diagram above, ``mpileaks`` depends on ``mpich`` with an unspecified "
"version, but packages can depend on other packages with *constraints* by "
"adding more specifiers.  For example, ``mpileaks`` could depend on "
"``mpich@1.2:`` if it can only build with version ``1.2`` or higher of "
"``mpich``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1178
msgid ""
"Windows Spec Syntax Caveats Windows has a few idiosyncrasies when it comes "
"to the Spack spec syntax and the use of certain shells Spack's spec "
"dependency syntax uses the carat (``^``) character, however this is an "
"escape string in CMD so it must be escaped with an additional carat (i.e. "
"``^^``). CMD also will attempt to interpret strings with ``=`` characters in "
"them. Any spec including this symbol must double quote the string."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1185
msgid ""
"Note: All of these issues are unique to CMD, they can be avoided by using "
"Powershell."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1187
msgid ""
"For more context on these caveats see the related issues: `carat <https://"
"github.com/spack/spack/issues/42833>`_ and `equals <https://github.com/spack/"
"spack/issues/43348>`_"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1189
msgid "Below are more details about the specifiers that you can add to specs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1195
msgid "Version specifier"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1197
msgid ""
"A version specifier ``pkg@<specifier>`` comes after a package name and "
"starts with ``@``. It can be something abstract that matches multiple known "
"versions, or a specific version. During concretization, Spack will pick the "
"optimal version within the spec's constraints according to policies set for "
"the particular Spack installation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1203
msgid ""
"The version specifier can be *a specific version*, such as ``@=1.0.0`` or "
"``@=1.2a7``. Or, it can be *a range of versions*, such as ``@1.0:1.5``. "
"Version ranges are inclusive, so this example includes both ``1.0`` and any "
"``1.5.x`` version. Version ranges can be unbounded, e.g. ``@:3`` means any "
"version up to and including ``3``. This would include ``3.4`` and "
"``3.4.2``.  Similarly, ``@4.2:`` means any version above and including "
"``4.2``.  As a short-hand, ``@3`` is equivalent to the range ``@3:3`` and "
"includes any version with major version ``3``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1212
msgid ""
"Versions are ordered lexicograpically by its components. For more details on "
"the order, see :ref:`the packaging guide <version-comparison>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1215
msgid ""
"Notice that you can distinguish between the specific version ``@=3.2`` and "
"the range ``@3.2``. This is useful for packages that follow a versioning "
"scheme that omits the zero patch version number: ``3.2``, ``3.2.1``, "
"``3.2.2``, etc. In general it is preferable to use the range syntax "
"``@3.2``, since ranges also match versions with one-off suffixes, such as "
"``3.2-custom``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1222
msgid ""
"A version specifier can also be a list of ranges and specific versions, "
"separated by commas.  For example, ``@1.0:1.5,=1.7.1`` matches any version "
"in the range ``1.0:1.5`` and the specific version ``1.7.1``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1228
msgid "Git versions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1230
msgid ""
"For packages with a ``git`` attribute, ``git`` references may be specified "
"instead of a numerical version i.e. branches, tags and commits. Spack will "
"stage and build based off the ``git`` reference provided.  Acceptable "
"syntaxes for this are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1235
msgid ""
" # commit hashes\n"
"foo@abcdef1234abcdef1234abcdef1234abcdef1234    # 40 character hashes are "
"automatically treated as git commits\n"
"foo@git.abcdef1234abcdef1234abcdef1234abcdef1234\n"
"\n"
" # branches and tags\n"
"foo@git.develop # use the develop branch\n"
"foo@git.0.19 # use the 0.19 tag"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1245
msgid ""
"Spack always needs to associate a Spack version with the git reference, "
"which is used for version comparison. This Spack version is heuristically "
"taken from the closest valid git tag among ancestors of the git ref."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1249
msgid ""
"Once a Spack version is associated with a git ref, it always printed with "
"the git ref.  For example, if the commit ``@git.abcdefg`` is tagged "
"``0.19``, then the spec will be shown as ``@git.abcdefg=0.19``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1253
msgid ""
"If the git ref is not exactly a tag, then the distance to the nearest tag is "
"also part of the resolved version. ``@git.abcdefg=0.19.git.8`` means that "
"the commit is 8 commits away from the ``0.19`` tag."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1257
msgid ""
"In cases where Spack cannot resolve a sensible version from a git ref, users "
"can specify the Spack version to use for the git ref. This is done by "
"appending ``=`` and the Spack version to the git ref. For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1261
msgid ""
"foo@git.my_ref=3.2 # use the my_ref tag or branch, but treat it as version "
"3.2 for version comparisons\n"
"foo@git.abcdef1234abcdef1234abcdef1234abcdef1234=develop # use the given "
"commit, but treat it as develop for version comparisons"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1266
msgid ""
"Details about how versions are compared and how Spack determines if one "
"version is less than another are discussed in the developer guide."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1271
msgid "Compiler specifier"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1273
msgid ""
"A compiler specifier comes somewhere after a package name and starts with "
"``%``.  It tells Spack what compiler(s) a particular package should be built "
"with.  After the ``%`` should come the name of some registered Spack "
"compiler.  This might include ``gcc``, or ``intel``, but the specific "
"compilers available depend on the site.  You can run ``spack compilers`` to "
"get a list; more on this below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1280
msgid ""
"The compiler spec can be followed by an optional *compiler version*. A "
"compiler version specifier looks exactly like a package version specifier.  "
"Version specifiers will associate with the nearest package name or compiler "
"specifier to their left in the spec."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1285
msgid ""
"If the compiler spec is omitted, Spack will choose a default compiler based "
"on site policies."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1293
msgid "Variants"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1295
msgid ""
"Variants are named options associated with a particular package. They are "
"optional, as each package must provide default values for each variant it "
"makes available. Variants can be specified using a flexible parameter syntax "
"``name=<value>``. For example, ``spack install mercury debug=True`` will "
"install mercury built with debug flags. The names of particular variants "
"available for a package depend on what was provided by the package author. "
"``spack info <package>`` will provide information on what build variants are "
"available."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1304
msgid ""
"For compatibility with earlier versions, variants which happen to be boolean "
"in nature can be specified by a syntax that represents turning options on "
"and off. For example, in the previous spec we could have supplied ``mercury "
"+debug`` with the same effect of enabling the debug compile time option for "
"the libelf package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1310
msgid ""
"Depending on the package a variant may have any default value.  For "
"``mercury`` here, ``debug`` is ``False`` by default, and we turned it on "
"with ``debug=True`` or ``+debug``.  If a variant is ``True`` by default you "
"can turn it off by either adding ``-name`` or ``~name`` to the spec."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1315
msgid ""
"There are two syntaxes here because, depending on context, ``~`` and ``-`` "
"may mean different things.  In most shells, the following will result in the "
"shell performing home directory substitution:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1319
msgid ""
"mpileaks ~debug   # shell may try to substitute this!\n"
"mpileaks~debug    # use this instead"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1324
msgid ""
"If there is a user called ``debug``, the ``~`` will be incorrectly "
"expanded.  In this situation, you would want to write ``libelf -debug``.  "
"However, ``-`` can be ambiguous when included after a package name without "
"spaces:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1329
msgid ""
"mpileaks-debug     # wrong!\n"
"mpileaks -debug    # right"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1334
msgid ""
"Spack allows the ``-`` character to be part of package names, so the above "
"will be interpreted as a request for the ``mpileaks-debug`` package, not a "
"request for ``mpileaks`` built without ``debug`` options.  In this scenario, "
"you should write ``mpileaks~debug`` to avoid ambiguity."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1340
msgid ""
"When spack normalizes specs, it prints them out with no spaces boolean "
"variants using the backwards compatibility syntax and uses only ``~`` for "
"disabled boolean variants.  The ``-`` and spaces on the command line are "
"provided for convenience and legibility."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1345
msgid ""
"Spack allows variants to propagate their value to the package's dependency "
"by using ``++``, ``--``, and ``~~`` for boolean variants. For example, for a "
"``debug`` variant:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1349
msgid ""
"mpileaks ++debug   # enabled debug will be propagated to dependencies\n"
"mpileaks +debug    # only mpileaks will have debug enabled"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1354
msgid ""
"To propagate the value of non-boolean variants Spack uses ``name==value``. "
"For example, for the ``stackstart`` variant:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1357
msgid ""
"mpileaks stackstart==4   # variant will be propagated to dependencies\n"
"mpileaks stackstart=4    # only mpileaks will have this variant value"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1362
msgid ""
"Spack also allows variants to be propagated from a package that does not "
"have that variant."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1368
msgid "Compiler Flags"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1370
msgid ""
"Compiler flags are specified using the same syntax as non-boolean variants, "
"but fulfill a different purpose. While the function of a variant is set by "
"the package, compiler flags are used by the compiler wrappers to inject "
"flags into the compile line of the build. Additionally, compiler flags can "
"be inherited by dependencies by using ``==``. ``spack install libdwarf "
"cppflags==\"-g\"`` will install both libdwarf and libelf with the ``-g`` "
"flag injected into their compile line."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1380
msgid ""
"versions of spack prior to 0.19.0 will propagate compiler flags using the "
"``=`` syntax."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1383
msgid ""
"Notice that the value of the compiler flags must be quoted if it contains "
"any spaces. Any of ``cppflags=-O3``, ``cppflags=\"-O3\"``, ``cppflags='-"
"O3'``, and ``cppflags=\"-O3 -fPIC\"`` are acceptable, but ``cppflags=-O3 -"
"fPIC`` is not. Additionally, if the value of the compiler flags is not the "
"last thing on the line, it must be followed by a space. The command ``spack "
"install libelf cppflags=\"-O3\"%intel`` will be interpreted as an attempt to "
"set ``cppflags=\"-O3%intel\"``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1391
msgid ""
"The six compiler flags are injected in the order of implicit make commands "
"in GNU Autotools. If all flags are set, the order is ``$cppflags $cflags|"
"$cxxflags $ldflags <command> $ldlibs`` for C and C++ and ``$fflags $cppflags "
"$ldflags <command> $ldlibs`` for Fortran."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1398
msgid "Compiler environment variables and additional RPATHs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1400
msgid ""
"Sometimes compilers require setting special environment variables to operate "
"correctly. Spack handles these cases by allowing custom environment "
"modifications in the ``environment`` attribute of the compiler configuration "
"section. See also the :ref:`configuration_environment_variables` section of "
"the configuration files docs for more information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1406
msgid ""
"It is also possible to specify additional ``RPATHs`` that the compiler will "
"add to all executables generated by that compiler.  This is useful for "
"forcing certain compilers to RPATH their own runtime libraries, so that "
"executables will run without the need to set ``LD_LIBRARY_PATH``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1411
msgid ""
"compilers:\n"
"  - compiler:\n"
"      spec: gcc@4.9.3\n"
"      paths:\n"
"        cc: /opt/gcc/bin/gcc\n"
"        c++: /opt/gcc/bin/g++\n"
"        f77: /opt/gcc/bin/gfortran\n"
"        fc: /opt/gcc/bin/gfortran\n"
"      environment:\n"
"        unset:\n"
"          - BAD_VARIABLE\n"
"        set:\n"
"          GOOD_VARIABLE_NUM: 1\n"
"          GOOD_VARIABLE_STR: good\n"
"        prepend_path:\n"
"          PATH: /path/to/binutils\n"
"        append_path:\n"
"          LD_LIBRARY_PATH: /opt/gcc/lib\n"
"      extra_rpaths:\n"
"      - /path/to/some/compiler/runtime/directory\n"
"      - /path/to/some/other/compiler/runtime/directory"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1438
msgid "Architecture specifiers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1440
msgid ""
"Each node in the dependency graph of a spec has an architecture attribute. "
"This attribute is a triplet of platform, operating system and processor. You "
"can specify the elements either separately, by using the reserved keywords "
"``platform``, ``os`` and ``target``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1445
msgid ""
"$ spack install libelf platform=linux\n"
"$ spack install libelf os=ubuntu18.04\n"
"$ spack install libelf target=broadwell"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1451
msgid ""
"Normally users don't have to bother specifying the architecture if they are "
"installing software for their current host, as in that case the values will "
"be detected automatically.  If you need fine-grained control over which "
"packages use which targets (or over *all* packages' default target), see :"
"ref:`package-preferences`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1462
msgid "Support for specific microarchitectures"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1464
msgid ""
"Spack knows how to detect and optimize for many specific microarchitectures "
"(including recent Intel, AMD and IBM chips) and encodes this information in "
"the ``target`` portion of the architecture specification. A complete list of "
"the microarchitectures known to Spack can be obtained in the following way:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1471
msgid ""
"When a spec is installed Spack matches the compiler being used with the "
"microarchitecture being targeted to inject appropriate optimization flags at "
"compile time. Giving a command such as the following:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1475
msgid "$ spack install zlib%gcc@9.0.1 target=icelake"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1479
msgid "will produce compilation lines similar to:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1481
msgid ""
"$ /usr/bin/gcc-9 -march=icelake-client -mtune=icelake-client -c ztest10532."
"c\n"
"$ /usr/bin/gcc-9 -march=icelake-client -mtune=icelake-client -c -fPIC -O2 "
"ztest10532.\n"
"..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1487
msgid ""
"where the flags ``-march=icelake-client -mtune=icelake-client`` are injected "
"by Spack based on the requested target and compiler."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1490
msgid ""
"If Spack knows that the requested compiler can't optimize for the current "
"target or can't build binaries for that target at all, it will exit with a "
"meaningful error message:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1493
msgid ""
"$ spack install zlib%gcc@5.5.0 target=icelake\n"
"==> Error: cannot produce optimized binary for micro-architecture "
"\"icelake\" with gcc@5.5.0 [supported compiler versions are 8:]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1498
msgid ""
"When instead an old compiler is selected on a recent enough "
"microarchitecture but there is no explicit ``target`` specification, Spack "
"will optimize for the best match it can find instead of failing:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1502
msgid ""
"$ spack arch\n"
"linux-ubuntu18.04-broadwell\n"
"\n"
"$ spack spec zlib%gcc@4.8\n"
"Input spec\n"
"--------------------------------\n"
"zlib%gcc@4.8\n"
"\n"
"Concretized\n"
"--------------------------------\n"
"zlib@1.2.11%gcc@4.8+optimize+pic+shared arch=linux-ubuntu18.04-haswell\n"
"\n"
"$ spack spec zlib%gcc@9.0.1\n"
"Input spec\n"
"--------------------------------\n"
"zlib%gcc@9.0.1\n"
"\n"
"Concretized\n"
"--------------------------------\n"
"zlib@1.2.11%gcc@9.0.1+optimize+pic+shared arch=linux-ubuntu18.04-broadwell"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1525
msgid ""
"In the snippet above, for instance, the microarchitecture was demoted to "
"``haswell`` when compiling with ``gcc@4.8`` since support to optimize for "
"``broadwell`` starts from ``gcc@4.9:``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1528
msgid ""
"Finally, if Spack has no information to match compiler and target, it will "
"proceed with the installation but avoid injecting any microarchitecture "
"specific flags."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1534
msgid ""
"Currently, Spack doesn't print any warning to the user if it has no "
"information on which optimization flags should be used for a given compiler. "
"This behavior might change in the future."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1542
msgid "Virtual dependencies"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1544
msgid ""
"The dependency graph for ``mpileaks`` we saw above wasn't *quite* accurate.  "
"``mpileaks`` uses MPI, which is an interface that has many different "
"implementations.  Above, we showed ``mpileaks`` and ``callpath`` depending "
"on ``mpich``, which is one *particular* implementation of MPI.  However, we "
"could build either with another implementation, such as ``openmpi`` or "
"``mvapich``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1551
msgid ""
"Spack represents interfaces like this using *virtual dependencies*. The real "
"dependency DAG for ``mpileaks`` looks like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1565
msgid ""
"Notice that ``mpich`` has now been replaced with ``mpi``. There is no *real* "
"MPI package, but some packages *provide* the MPI interface, and these "
"packages can be substituted in for ``mpi`` when ``mpileaks`` is built."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1570
msgid ""
"You can see what virtual packages a particular package provides by getting "
"info on it:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1575
msgid ""
"Spack is unique in that its virtual packages can be versioned, just like "
"regular packages.  A particular version of a package may provide a "
"particular version of a virtual package, and we can see above that ``mpich`` "
"versions ``1`` and above provide all ``mpi`` interface versions up to ``1``, "
"and ``mpich`` versions ``3`` and above provide ``mpi`` versions up to "
"``3``.  A package can *depend on* a particular version of a virtual package, "
"e.g. if an application needs MPI-2 functions, it can depend on ``mpi@2:`` to "
"indicate that it needs some implementation that provides MPI-2 functions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1587
msgid "Constraining virtual packages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1589
msgid ""
"When installing a package that depends on a virtual package, you can opt to "
"specify the particular provider you want to use, or you can let Spack pick.  "
"For example, if you just type this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1597
msgid ""
"Then spack will pick a provider for you according to site policies. If you "
"really want a particular version, say ``mpich``, then you could run this "
"instead:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1601
msgid "$ spack install mpileaks ^mpich"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1605
msgid ""
"This forces spack to use some version of ``mpich`` for its implementation.  "
"As always, you can be even more specific and require a particular ``mpich`` "
"version:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1609
msgid "$ spack install mpileaks ^mpich@3"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1613
msgid ""
"The ``mpileaks`` package in particular only needs MPI-1 commands, so any MPI "
"implementation will do.  If another package depends on ``mpi@2`` and you try "
"to give it an insufficient MPI implementation (e.g., one that provides only "
"``mpi@:1``), then Spack will raise an error.  Likewise, if you try to plug "
"in some package that doesn't provide MPI, Spack will raise an error."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1622
msgid "Explicit binding of virtual dependencies"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1624
msgid ""
"There are packages that provide more than just one virtual dependency. When "
"interacting with them, users might want to utilize just a subset of what "
"they could provide, and use other providers for virtuals they need."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1628
msgid ""
"It is possible to be more explicit and tell Spack which dependency should "
"provide which virtual, using a special syntax:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1631
msgid ""
"$ spack spec strumpack ^[virtuals=mpi] intel-parallel-studio+mkl "
"^[virtuals=lapack] openblas"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1635
msgid "Concretizing the spec above produces the following DAG:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1641
msgid ""
"where ``intel-parallel-studio`` *could* provide ``mpi``, ``lapack``, and "
"``blas`` but is used only for the former. The ``lapack`` and ``blas`` "
"dependencies are satisfied by ``openblas``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1646
msgid "Specifying Specs by Hash"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1648
msgid ""
"Complicated specs can become cumbersome to enter on the command line, "
"especially when many of the qualifications are necessary to distinguish "
"between similar installs. To avoid this, when referencing an existing spec, "
"Spack allows you to reference specs by their hash. We previously discussed "
"the spec hash that Spack computes. In place of a spec in any command, "
"substitute ``/<hash>`` where ``<hash>`` is any amount from the beginning of "
"a spec hash."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1656
msgid ""
"For example, lets say that you accidentally installed two different "
"``mvapich2`` installations. If you want to uninstall one of them but don't "
"know what the difference is, you can run:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1660
msgid ""
"$ spack find --long mvapich2\n"
"==> 2 installed packages.\n"
"-- linux-centos7-x86_64 / gcc@6.3.0 ----------\n"
"qmt35td mvapich2@2.2%gcc\n"
"er3die3 mvapich2@2.2%gcc"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1669
msgid "You can then uninstall the latter installation using:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1671
msgid "$ spack uninstall /er3die3"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1676
msgid ""
"Or, if you want to build with a specific installation as a dependency, you "
"can use:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1679
msgid "$ spack install trilinos ^/er3die3"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1684
msgid ""
"If the given spec hash is sufficiently long as to be unique, Spack will "
"replace the reference with the spec to which it refers. Otherwise, it will "
"prompt for a more qualified hash."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1688
msgid ""
"Note that this will not work to reinstall a dependency uninstalled by "
"``spack uninstall --force``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1695
msgid "``spack providers``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1697
msgid ""
"You can see what packages provide a particular virtual package using ``spack "
"providers``.  If you wanted to see what packages provide ``mpi``, you would "
"just run:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1703
msgid ""
"And if you *only* wanted to see packages that provide MPI-2, you would add a "
"version specifier to the spec:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1708
msgid ""
"Notice that the package versions that provide insufficient MPI versions are "
"now filtered out."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1714
msgid "Deprecating insecure packages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1716
msgid ""
"``spack deprecate`` allows for the removal of insecure packages with minimal "
"impact to their dependents."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1721
msgid ""
"The ``spack deprecate`` command is designed for use only in extraordinary "
"circumstances. This is a VERY big hammer to be used with care."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1725
msgid ""
"The ``spack deprecate`` command will remove one package and replace it with "
"another by replacing the deprecated package's prefix with a link to the "
"deprecator package's prefix."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1731
msgid ""
"The ``spack deprecate`` command makes no promises about binary "
"compatibility. It is up to the user to ensure the deprecator is suitable for "
"the deprecated package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1735
msgid ""
"Spack tracks concrete deprecated specs and ensures that no future packages "
"concretize to a deprecated spec."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1738
msgid ""
"The first spec given to the ``spack deprecate`` command is the package to "
"deprecate. It is an abstract spec that must describe a single installed "
"package. The second spec argument is the deprecator spec. By default it must "
"be an abstract spec that describes a single installed package, but with the "
"``-i/--install-deprecator`` it can be any abstract spec that Spack will "
"install and then use as the deprecator. The ``-I/--no-install-deprecator`` "
"option will ensure the default behavior."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1747
msgid ""
"By default, ``spack deprecate`` will deprecate all dependencies of the "
"deprecated spec, replacing each by the dependency of the same name in the "
"deprecator spec. The ``-d/--dependencies`` option will ensure the default, "
"while the ``-D/--no-dependencies`` option will deprecate only the root of "
"the deprecate spec in favor of the root of the deprecator spec."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1754
msgid ""
"``spack deprecate`` can use symbolic links or hard links. The default "
"behavior is symbolic links, but the ``-l/--link-type`` flag can take options "
"``hard`` or ``soft``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1760
msgid "Verifying installations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1762
msgid ""
"The ``spack verify`` command can be used to verify the validity of Spack-"
"installed packages any time after installation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1765
msgid ""
"At installation time, Spack creates a manifest of every file in the "
"installation prefix. For links, Spack tracks the mode, ownership, and "
"destination. For directories, Spack tracks the mode, and ownership. For "
"files, Spack tracks the mode, ownership, modification time, hash, and size. "
"The Spack verify command will check, for every file in each package, whether "
"any of those attributes have changed. It will also check for newly added "
"files or deleted files from the installation prefix. Spack can either check "
"all installed packages using the `-a,--all` or accept specs listed on the "
"command line to verify."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1776
msgid ""
"The ``spack verify`` command can also verify for individual files that they "
"haven't been altered since installation time. If the given file is not in a "
"Spack installation prefix, Spack will report that it is not owned by any "
"package. To check individual files instead of specs, use the ``-f,--files`` "
"option."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1782
msgid ""
"Spack installation manifests are part of the tarball signed by Spack for "
"binary package distribution. When installed from a binary package, Spack "
"uses the packaged installation manifest instead of creating one at install "
"time."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1787
msgid ""
"The ``spack verify`` command also accepts the ``-l,--local`` option to check "
"only local packages (as opposed to those used transparently from "
"``upstream`` spack instances) and the ``-j,--json`` option to output machine-"
"readable json data for any errors."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1794
msgid "Filesystem requirements"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1796
msgid ""
"By default, Spack needs to be run from a filesystem that supports ``flock`` "
"locking semantics.  Nearly all local filesystems and recent versions of NFS "
"support this, but parallel filesystems or NFS volumes may be configured "
"without ``flock`` support enabled.  You can determine how your filesystems "
"are mounted with ``mount``.  The output for a Lustre filesystem might look "
"like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1803
msgid ""
"$ mount | grep lscratch\n"
"mds1-lnet0@o2ib100:/lsd on /p/lscratchd type lustre (rw,nosuid,lazystatfs,"
"flock)\n"
"mds2-lnet0@o2ib100:/lse on /p/lscratche type lustre (rw,nosuid,lazystatfs,"
"flock)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1809
msgid "Note the ``flock`` option on both Lustre mounts."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1811
msgid ""
"If you do not see this or a similar option for your filesystem, you have a "
"few options. First, you can move your Spack installation to a filesystem "
"that supports locking. Second, you could ask your system administrator to "
"enable ``flock`` for your filesystem."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1816
msgid "If none of those work, you can disable locking in one of two ways:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1818
msgid ""
"Run Spack with the ``-L`` or ``--disable-locks`` option to disable locks on "
"a call-by-call basis."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1820
msgid ""
"Edit :ref:`config.yaml <config-yaml>` and set the ``locks`` option to "
"``false`` to always disable locking."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1825
msgid ""
"If you disable locking, concurrent instances of Spack will have no way to "
"avoid stepping on each other.  You must ensure that there is only **one** "
"instance of Spack running at a time.  Otherwise, Spack may end up with a "
"corrupted database file, or you may not be able to see all installed "
"packages in commands like ``spack find``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1831
msgid ""
"If you are unfortunate enough to run into this situation, you may be able to "
"fix it by running ``spack reindex``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1834
msgid "This issue typically manifests with the error below:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1836
msgid ""
"$ ./spack find\n"
"Traceback (most recent call last):\n"
"File \"./spack\", line 176, in <module>\n"
"  main()\n"
"File \"./spack\", line 154,' in main\n"
"  return_val = command(parser, args)\n"
"File \"./spack/lib/spack/spack/cmd/find.py\", line 170, in find\n"
"  specs = set(spack.installed_db.query(\\**q_args))\n"
"File \"./spack/lib/spack/spack/database.py\", line 551, in query\n"
"  with self.read_transaction():\n"
"File \"./spack/lib/spack/spack/database.py\", line 598, in __enter__\n"
"  if self._enter() and self._acquire_fn:\n"
"File \"./spack/lib/spack/spack/database.py\", line 608, in _enter\n"
"  return self._db.lock.acquire_read(self._timeout)\n"
"File \"./spack/lib/spack/llnl/util/lock.py\", line 103, in acquire_read\n"
"  self._lock(fcntl.LOCK_SH, timeout)   # can raise LockError.\n"
"File \"./spack/lib/spack/llnl/util/lock.py\", line 64, in _lock\n"
"  fcntl.lockf(self._fd, op | fcntl.LOCK_NB)\n"
"IOError: [Errno 38] Function not implemented"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1858
msgid "A nicer error message is TBD in future versions of Spack."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1862
msgid "Troubleshooting"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1864
msgid "The ``spack audit`` command:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1868
msgid ""
"can be used to detect a number of configuration issues. This command detects "
"configuration settings which might not be strictly wrong but are not likely "
"to be useful outside of special cases."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1872
msgid ""
"It can also be used to detect dependency issues with packages - for example "
"cases where a package constrains a dependency with a variant that doesn't "
"exist (in this case Spack could report the problem ahead of time but "
"automatically performing the check would slow down most runs of Spack)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1877
msgid ""
"A detailed list of the checks currently implemented for each subcommand can "
"be printed with:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1882
msgid ""
"Depending on the use case, users might run the appropriate subcommands to "
"obtain diagnostics. Issues, if found, are reported to stdout:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1885
msgid ""
"% spack audit packages lammps\n"
"PKG-DIRECTIVES: 1 issue found\n"
"1. lammps: wrong variant in \"conflicts\" directive\n"
"    the variant 'adios' does not exist\n"
"    in /home/spack/spack/var/spack/repos/builtin/packages/lammps/package.py"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1896
msgid "Getting Help"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1902
msgid "``spack help``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1904
msgid ""
"If you don't find what you need here, the ``help`` subcommand will print out "
"out a list of *all* of spack's options and subcommands:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1909
msgid ""
"Adding an argument, e.g. ``spack help <subcommand>``, will print out usage "
"information for a particular subcommand:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic_usage.rst:1914
msgid ""
"Alternately, you can use ``spack --help`` in place of ``spack help``, or "
"``spack <subcommand> --help`` to get help on a particular subcommand."
msgstr ""
